title: For Sale:  Steyr Männlicher .308
postcontent:
I have a very fine Steyr Mannlicher in .308 with a beautiful dark full length walnut stock. Its the finest piece of wood I have ever seen on a production rifle. The rifle features a set trigger and I had the gun smith at Steyr America here in Bessemer mount a Swarovski Z5 3.5-18 scope on it with Steyr Quick Release Scope Mounts which retian their zero even during detachment, they also serviced it for me, its in great condition. The scope has a ballistic reticle sighted in with additional adjustment horizontal cross hairs for 275, 320, 380, 430, 480, 520, 560, 600, and 640 yards; the main cross hair is zeroed at 200 yards and the iron sight are zerod for 100yrds which means they are also on at 25yrds and only a bit high at 50; all of this is for 165 grain Federeal Fusion ammo but I also have charts for Hornady and other manufactured ammunitions. However tyne rille is sighted in with the Federal Fusion trophy bonded tip ammo. I have only fired three boxes of ammunition in this rifle since and its in great condition. 

I'm asking top price for this rifle and its worth it. It is in excellent condition, short of a custom gun this is the finest rifle on earth. Weatherby actions might fire more rounds through larger cannon like barrels, many people make much cheaper rifles but no one makes a smoother action, a faster pointing, or a more accurate production rifle, and few custom gunsmiths could do any better. This is an extremely light rifle, even with the scope. I have a Jeff Cooper Scout and its about the same weight; scopes included this one is acutely lighter. 
The scope I am happy to keep but I will sell it; the scope mounts alone cost me $500 before labor. I paid over $2,000 for this rifle at Mark's Outdoors, I'm not going to sell it for any less. I'm not looking to trade anything in particular but I'm willing to listen to good offers for other fine rifles, a nice M1 Carbine, or pistols either made in America or Germany .22, .45 ACP, or 10mm; and four wheelers. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Steyr .308 "Jeff Cooper Scout Rifle"
postcontent:
This is a Styer .308 rifle designed by Jeff Cooper in his infamous Scout Rifle configuration. If your not familiar with his scout rifle concept it is an ultralight rifle with a spare magazine that clips into the butt of the stock and a pica-tiny rail that allows you to mount a normal scope traditionally or a long eye relief scope forward. It also sports collapsable iron sights, a fluted barrel, and detachable sling. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scout_rifle
      This rifle I bought last year from Marks Outdoors Sports here in Birmingham. I have mounted a Zeiss Victory FL Diavari 6–24x72. With a lighted mil-dot reticle (#43) with normal eye relief in the traditional configuration. The scope would cost over $5,000 new; I am prepared to breakup the set but it has been professionally mounted and sighted in at 200 yards. I've only fired 2.5 boxes of ammo throughou this rifle since it came form the factory; Styer's American headquarters is here in Alabama, I had them clean and service the gun and verify its superb condition. So no low ballers please. I will not part with the scoop for less than $4,000.00
I paid over $2,000 for this rifle at Mark's Outdoors, I'm not going to sell it for any less either. I'm sure there are several of these available with a thousand rounds throughout hem. I'm not looking to trade anything in particular but I'm willing to listen to good offers for trades on other fine rifles, a nice M1 Carbine, or pistols either made in America or Germany .22, .45 ACP, or 10mm; and four wheelers. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale/Trade:  100 year old German Mauser 25 ACP pistol
postcontent:
Norman, REDACTED, $200 OBO
Hey all,
I have a really old German Mauser 25 auto pistol that I picked up in trade. I got it with the intent of doing some work on it and having it be a new caliber, but I have had some things come up that will be eating too much of my time. So, i would rather pass it along and let someone else enjoy her themselves. It is a model 1914 Mauser 25 acp. The serial number dated it to around 1916-17 (best i could tell at least). It is actually a comparatively low serial number (5 digit serial). It is in average/decent condition for its age but not “terrible” compared to what I’ve seen elsewhere. Has heavy bluing wear, dings, and a  crack in grip, but is still a decent looking gun. The main issue this one has is that it jams up feeding/ejecting almost every shot. It is possibly as simple as replacing a spring or giving it a really good polishing on the feed ramp/throat. It could even be that the only 25 auto ammo i had to test her with was some cheap/older blazer stuff, which i have had some issues with in other guns. Either way, I simply don’t have the time to get her “fixed up” or i would and then keep her (or sell for double! haha). I know that in this condition and shooting fine they sell for substantially more than what I am asking. Also, I have found most replacement parts online from normal places, so this could be a fun and easy little project!
